Definition 3.1. A partial injection is a partial function that is injective, wherever it is defined. More precisely, it(s graph) is a relation $R\subseteq X\times Y$ such that for each $x$ there is at most one $y$ with $(x,y)\in R$, and for each $y$ there is at most one $x$ with $(y,x)\in R$. Sets and partial injections form a category $\mathbf{PInj}$ under composition of relations $S\circ R=\{(x,z)\mid\exists y\colon(x,y)\in R,(y,z)\in S\}$.
Definition 4.1. There is a functor $\ell^{2}\colon\mathbf{PInj}\to\mathbf{Hilb}$, acting on a set $X$ as $\ell^{2}(X)=\{\varphi\colon X\to\mathbb{C}\mid\sum_{x\in X}|\varphi(x)|^{2}<% \infty\},$ which is a well-defined Hilbert under the inner product $\langle\varphi\,|\,\psi\rangle=\sum_{x\in X}\overline{\varphi(x)}\psi(x)$. The action on morphisms sends a partial injection $(\smash{\xymatrix@1{X&F\ar@{>->}|-{f_{1}}[l]\ar@{>->}|-{f_{2}}[r]&Y}})$ to the linear function $\ell^{2}f\colon\ell^{2}(X)\to\ell^{2}(Y)$ determined informally by $\ell^{2}f=(\underline{\phantom{n}})\circ f^{\dagger}$. Explicitly, $(\ell^{2}f)(\varphi)(y)=\sum_{x\in f_{2}^{-1}(y)}\varphi(f_{1}(x)).$
Definition 5.10. A functor $F\colon\mathbf{C}\to\mathbf{D}$ is essentially full when for each morphism $g$ in $\mathbf{D}$ there exist $f$ in $\mathbf{C}$ and $u,v$ in $\mathbf{C}_{\cong}$ such that $g=v\circ Ff\circ u$. It follows that the essential image of such a functor is all of $\mathbf{D}$.
Definition 3.10. An inverse category is a category $\mathbf{C}$ in which every morphism $f\colon X\to Y$ allows a unique morphism $f^{\dagger}\colon Y\to X$ satisfying $f=ff^{\dagger}f$ and $f^{\dagger}=f^{\dagger}ff^{\dagger}$. Equivalently, it is a dagger category satisfying $f=ff^{\dagger}f$ and $pq=qp$ for idempotents $p,q\colon X\to X$. The proof of equivalence of these two statements is the same as for inverse semigroups (see [22, Theorem 1.1.3] or [8, Theorem 2.20]). Inverse categories are a special case of restriction categories [8]. The category $\mathbf{PInj}$ is an inverse category under its dagger (see 3.2). The following categorification of the Wagner–Preston theorem [22, Theorem 1.5.1] shows that it is in fact a representative one. See also [8, 3.4].
Definition 2.1. We are interested in the category $\mathbf{Hilb}$, whose objects are complex Hilbert spaces, and whose morphisms are continuous linear functions.
Definition 5.2. For a category $\mathbf{C}$, denote by $\mathbf{C}_{\cong}$ the groupoid with the same objects as $\mathbf{C}$ whose morphisms are the isomorphisms of $\mathbf{C}$. The category $\mathbf{Hilb}_{\cong}$ is a groupoid, and hence has a dagger. It carries two dagger symmetric monoidal structures: $\oplus$ and $\otimes$. Because having (co)limits only depends on a skeleton of the specifying diagram, $\mathbf{Hilb}_{\cong}$ does not have (co)equalizers, nor (finite) (co)products, but does have directed (co)limits.
Definition 1.5. For each $f\in{}_{G}\mathit{set}(X,Y)$ and $p\in{}_{G}\mathit{set}(A,X)$, the canonical exponential diagram generated by $f$ and $p$ is the commutative diagram $\xy(-14,6)*+{X}="0";(-14,-6)*+{Y}="2";(-1,6)*+{A}="4";(9,6)*+{}="5";(18,4.7)*+% {X\underset{Y}{\times}\Pi_{f}(A)}="6";(16,2)*+{}="7";(16,-6)*+{\Pi_{f}(A)}="8"% ;(0,0)*+{\mathit{exp}}="10";{\ar_{f}"0";"2"};{\ar_{p}"4";"0"};{\ar_{>}>>>>{e}"% 5";"4"};{\ar^{>}>>>{f^{\prime}}"7";"8"};{\ar^{\pi}"8";"2"};\endxy$ where $\Pi_{f}(A)=\Set{(y,\sigma)}{\begin{array}[]{l}y\in Y,\\ \sigma\colon f^{-1}(y)\rightarrow A\ \,\text{is a map of sets},\\ p\circ\sigma\ \,\text{is identity on}\ f^{-1}(y)\end{array}},$ $\pi(y,\sigma)=y,\ \ \ \ \ e(x,(y,\sigma))=\sigma(x),$ and $f^{\prime}$ is the pull-back of $f$ by $\pi$. A diagram in ${}_{G}\mathit{set}$ isomorphic to one of the canonical exponential diagrams is called an exponential diagram. For the properties of exponential diagrams, see [8].
Definition 3.1. A Tambara functor $\mathcal{H}$ is a Hopf Tambara functor if it is equipped with morphisms in $\mathit{Tam}(G)$ $\Delta\colon\mathcal{H}\rightarrow\mathcal{H}\underset{\Omega}{\otimes}% \mathcal{H},\quad\varepsilon\colon\mathcal{H}\rightarrow T,\quad\eta\colon% \mathcal{H}\rightarrow\mathcal{H},$ satisfying $\displaystyle(\Delta\underset{\Omega}{\otimes}\mathrm{id})\circ\Delta=(\mathrm% {id}\underset{\Omega}{\otimes}\Delta)\circ\Delta,$ $\displaystyle(\varepsilon\underset{\Omega}{\otimes}\mathrm{id})\circ\Delta=% \mathrm{id}=(\mathrm{id}\underset{\Omega}{\otimes}\varepsilon)\circ\Delta,$ $\displaystyle\nabla\circ(\eta\underset{\Omega}{\otimes}\mathrm{id})\circ\Delta% =\varepsilon\circ\iota=\nabla\circ(\mathrm{id}\underset{\Omega}{\otimes}\eta)% \circ\Delta.$ If $(\mathcal{H},\Delta,\varepsilon,\eta)$ and $(\mathcal{H}^{\prime},\Delta^{\prime},\varepsilon^{\prime},\eta^{\prime})$ are Hopf Tambara functors, then a morphism $\varphi\in\mathit{Tam}(G)(\mathcal{H},\mathcal{H}^{\prime})$ is a morphism of Hopf Tambara functors if it satisfies $\Delta^{\prime}\circ\varphi=(\varphi\underset{\Omega}{\otimes}f)\circ\Delta,% \quad\varepsilon^{\prime}\circ\varphi=\varepsilon,\quad\eta^{\prime}\circ% \varphi=\varphi\circ\eta.$ We denote the category of Hopf Tambara functors by $\mathit{Hopf}(G)$.
Definition 1.1. An additive contravariant functor $F$ on $G$ means a contravariant functor $F\colon{}_{G}\mathit{set}\rightarrow\mathit{Set},$ which sends coproducts in ${}_{G}\mathit{set}$ to products in $\mathit{Set}$.
Definition 1.10. Fix a Tambara functor $T\in\mathrm{Ob}(\mathit{Tam}(G))$. A $T$-Tambara functor is a pair $(S,\sigma)$ of a Tambara functor $S$ and $\sigma\in\mathit{Tam}(G)(T,S)$. We often represent $(S,\sigma)$ merely by $S$. If $(S,\sigma)$ and $(S^{\prime},\sigma^{\prime})$ are $T$-Tambara functors, then a morphism $\varphi$ from $(S,\sigma)$ to $(S^{\prime},\sigma^{\prime})$ is a morphism $\varphi\in\mathit{Tam}(G)(S,S^{\prime})$ satisfying $\sigma^{\prime}=\varphi\circ\sigma$. The category of $T$-Tambara functors is denoted by $T\text{-}\mathit{Tam}(G)$. Remark that $\Omega\text{-}\mathit{Tam}(G)$ is nothing other than $\mathit{Tam}(G)$. By Remark 1.9, for any $T,S\in\mathrm{Ob}(\mathit{Tam}(G))$, their tensor product $T\underset{\Omega}{\otimes}S$ can be naturally regarded as a $T$-Tambara functor $(T\underset{\Omega}{\otimes}S,\iota_{T})$, or a $S$-Tambara functor $(T\underset{\Omega}{\otimes}S,\iota_{S})$.
Definition 1.2. A semi-Mackey functor $M$ on $G$ is a pair $M=(M^{\ast},M_{\ast})$ of a covariant functor $M_{\ast}\colon{}_{G}\mathit{set}\rightarrow\mathit{Set}$ and an additive contravariant functor $M^{\ast}\colon{}_{G}\mathit{set}\rightarrow\mathit{Set},$ satisfying $M^{\ast}(X)=M_{\ast}(X)$ for any $X\in\mathrm{Ob}({}_{G}\mathit{set})$, and the following Mackey condition: • (Mackey condition) If we are given a pull-back diagram $\xy(-6,6)*+{X^{\prime}}="0";(6,6)*+{Y^{\prime}}="2";(-6,-6)*+{X}="4";(6,-6)*+{% Y}="6";(0,0)*+{\square}="8";{\ar^{f^{\prime}}"0";"2"};{\ar_{x}"0";"4"};{\ar^{y% }"2";"6"};{\ar_{f}"4";"6"};\endxy$ in ${}_{G}\mathit{set}$, then $\xy(-12,7)*+{M(X^{\prime})}="0";(12,7)*+{M(Y^{\prime})}="2";(-12,-7)*+{M(X)}="% 4";(12,-7)*+{M(Y)}="6";{\ar_{M^{\ast}(f^{\prime})}"2";"0"};{\ar_{M_{\ast}(x)}"% 0";"4"};{\ar^{M_{\ast}(y)}"2";"6"};{\ar^{M^{\ast}(f)}"6";"4"};{\ar@{}|% \circlearrowright"0";"6"};\endxy$ is commutative. Here we put $M(X)=M^{\ast}(X)=M_{\ast}(X)$ for each $X\in\mathrm{Ob}({}_{G}\mathit{set})$. Those $M_{\ast}(f)$ and $M^{\ast}(f)$ for morphisms $f$ in ${}_{G}\mathit{set}$ are called structure morphisms of $M$. For each $f\in{}_{G}\mathit{set}(X,Y)$, $M^{\ast}(f)$ is called the restriction, and $M_{\ast}(f)$ is called the transfer along $f$. If $M$ is a semi-Mackey functor, then $M^{\ast}$ and $M_{\ast}$ become naturally functors to $\mathit{Mon}$. For semi-Mackey functors $M$ and $N$, a morphism from $M$ to $N$ is a family of monoid homomorphisms $\varphi=\{\varphi_{X}\colon M(X)\rightarrow N(X)\}_{X\in\mathrm{Ob}({}_{G}% \mathit{set})},$ natural with respect to both of the contravariant and the covariant parts. The category of semi-Mackey functors is denoted by $\mathit{SMack}(G)$. If $M(X)$ is an abelian group for each $X\in\mathrm{Ob}({}_{G}\mathit{set})$, namely if $M^{\ast}$ and $M_{\ast}$ are functors to $\mathit{Ab}$, then a semi-Mackey functor $M=(M^{\ast},M_{\ast})$ is called a Mackey functor. The full subcategory of Mackey functors in $\mathit{SMack}(G)$ is denoted by $\mathit{Mack}(G)$.
Definition 2.1 (Theorem 2.9 in [7]). Let $Q$ be a finite $G$-monoid, and $T$ be a Tambara functor on $G$. In [7], $T_{Q}\in\mathrm{Ob}(\mathit{Tam}(G))$ is defined by $T_{Q}(X)=T(X\times Q)$ for each $X\in\mathrm{Ob}({}_{G}\mathit{set})$, whose structure morphisms are given by $\displaystyle(T_{Q})^{\ast}(f)$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle T^{\ast}(f\times Q)$ $\displaystyle(T_{Q})_{+}(f)$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle T_{+}(f\times Q)$ $\displaystyle(T_{Q})_{\bullet}(f)$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle T_{+}(\mu_{f})\circ T_{\bullet}(f^{\prime})\circ T^{\ast}(e)$ for each morphism $f\in{}_{G}\mathit{set}(X,Y)$. Here, $\xy(-24,6)*+{X}="0";(-24,-6)*+{Y}="2";(-4,6)*+{X\times Q}="4";(24,6)*+{X\times% _{Y}\Pi_{f}(X\times Q)}="6";(24,-6)*+{\Pi_{f}(X\times Q)}="8";(0,0)*+{\mathit{% exp}}="10";{\ar_{f}"0";"2"};{\ar_{p_{X}}"4";"0"};{\ar_{<}<<<{e}"6";"4"};{\ar^{% f^{\prime}}"6";"8"};{\ar^{\pi}"8";"2"};\endxy$ is the canonical exponential diagram with $p_{X}\colon X\times Q\rightarrow X$ the projection, and $\mu_{f}\colon\Pi_{f}(X\times Q)\rightarrow Y\times Q$ is the morphism defined by $\mu_{f}(y,\sigma)=(y,\prod_{x\in f^{-1}(y)}\!p_{Q}\circ\sigma(x)),$ where $p_{Q}\colon X\times Q\rightarrow Q$ is the projection. Especially if $T=\Omega$, then $\Omega_{Q}$ is called the crossed Burnside ring functor.
Definition 1.6. A semi-Tambara functor $T$ on $G$ is a triplet $T=(T^{\ast},T_{+},T_{\bullet})$ of two covariant functors $T_{+}\colon{}_{G}\mathit{set}\rightarrow\mathit{Set},\ \ T_{\bullet}\colon{}_{% G}\mathit{set}\rightarrow\mathit{Set}$ and one additive contravariant functor $T^{\ast}\colon{}_{G}\mathit{set}\rightarrow\mathit{Set}$ which satisfies the following. (1) $T^{\alpha}=(T^{\ast},T_{+})$ and $T^{\mu}=(T^{\ast},T_{\bullet})$ are objects in $\mathit{SMack}(G)$. $T^{\alpha}$ is called the additive part of $T$, and $T^{\mu}$ is called the multiplicative part of $T$. (2) (Distributive law) If we are given an exponential diagram $\xy(-12,6)*+{X}="0";(-12,-6)*+{Y}="2";(0,6)*+{A}="4";(12,6)*+{Z}="6";(12,-6)*+% {B}="8";(0,0)*+{exp}="10";{\ar_{f}"0";"2"};{\ar_{p}"4";"0"};{\ar_{\lambda}"6";% "4"};{\ar^{\rho}"6";"8"};{\ar^{q}"8";"2"};\endxy$ in ${}_{G}\mathit{set}$, then $\xy(-18,7)*+{T(X)}="0";(-18,-7)*+{T(Y)}="2";(0,7)*+{T(A)}="4";(18,7)*+{T(Z)}="% 6";(18,-7)*+{T(B)}="8";{\ar_{T_{\bullet}(f)}"0";"2"};{\ar_{T_{+}(p)}"4";"0"};{% \ar^{T^{\ast}(\lambda)}"4";"6"};{\ar^{T_{\bullet}(\rho)}"6";"8"};{\ar^{T_{+}(q% )}"8";"2"};{\ar@{}|\circlearrowright"0";"8"};\endxy$ is commutative. If $T=(T^{\ast},T_{+},T_{\bullet})$ is a semi-Tambara functor, then $T(X)$ becomes a semi-ring for each $X\in\mathrm{Ob}({}_{G}\mathit{set})$, whose additive (resp. multiplicative) monoid structure is induced from that on $T^{\alpha}(X)$ (resp. $T^{\mu}(X)$). Those $T^{\ast}(f),T_{+}(f),T_{\bullet}(f)$ for morphisms $f$ in ${}_{G}\mathit{set}$ are called structure morphisms of $T$. For each $f\in{}_{G}\mathit{set}(X,Y)$, • $T^{\ast}(f)\colon T(Y)\rightarrow T(X)$ is a semi-ring homomorphism, called the restriction along $f$. • $T_{+}(f)\colon T(X)\rightarrow T(Y)$ is an additive homomorphism, called the additive transfer along $f$. • $T_{\bullet}(f)\colon T(X)\rightarrow T(Y)$ is a multiplicative homomorphism, called the multiplicative transfer along $f$. $T^{\ast}(f),T_{+}(f),T_{\bullet}(f)$ are often abbreviated to $f^{\ast},f_{+},f_{\bullet}$. A morphism of semi-Tambara functors $\varphi\colon T\rightarrow S$ is a family of semi-ring homomorphisms $\varphi=\{\varphi_{X}\colon T(X)\rightarrow S(X)\}_{X\in\mathrm{Ob}({}_{G}% \mathit{set})},$ natural with respect to all of the contravariant and the covariant parts. We denote the category of semi-Tambara functors by $\mathit{STam}(G)$. If $T(X)$ is a ring for each $X\in\mathrm{Ob}({}_{G}\mathit{set})$, then a semi-Tambara functor $T$ is called a Tambara functor. The full subcategory of Tambara functors in $\mathit{STam}(G)$ is denoted by $\mathit{Tam}(G)$.
Definition 3.3. Let $\mathcal{H}$ be a Hopf Tambara functor. For each $X\in\mathrm{Ob}({}_{G}\mathit{set})$, we call an element $m\in\mathcal{H}(X)$ group-like if it satisfies $\displaystyle\Delta_{X}(m)=[m\otimes m]_{(X,\mathrm{id}_{X})}$ $\displaystyle\quad\text{in}\ \ (\mathcal{H}\underset{\Omega}{\otimes}\mathcal{% H})(X),$ $\displaystyle\varepsilon_{X}(m)=1$ $\displaystyle\quad\text{in}\ \ \Omega(X).$
Definition 3.2. Let $F:\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{C}$ be an endofunctor of an additive category $\mathcal{C}$. The orbit category $\mathcal{C}/\langle F\rangle$ of $\mathcal{C}$ by $F$ is the category with the same objects as $\mathcal{C}$ and the spaces of morphisms $\operatorname{Hom}\nolimits_{\mathcal{C}/\langle F\rangle}(M,N)=\operatorname{% colim}\nolimits_{l\in\operatorname{\mathbb{N}}\nolimits}\bigoplus_{i\in% \operatorname{\mathbb{N}}\nolimits}\operatorname{Hom}\nolimits_{\mathcal{C}}(F% ^{i}(M),F^{l}(N)).$
Definition 5.5. We call an indecomposable object $X$ in $\mathcal{C}_{RQ}$ lattice-like, if there is a lattice $L$ such that $X$ is isomorphic to $\Gamma\otimes^{L}_{RQ}L$ or $X$ is isomorphic to $\Sigma\Gamma\otimes^{L}_{RQ}P$ for a projective indecomposable $RQ$-module $P$.
Definition 6.1. A cluster-tilting object $T$ is a rigid object in $\mathcal{C}_{RQ}$ such that $T$ has $n$ indecomposable direct summands which are pairwise non-isomorphic. Let $T^{\prime}$ be another cluster-tilting object. The pair $(T,T^{\prime})$ is called a mutation pair if $T$ and $T^{\prime}$ have exactly $n-1$ isomorphic indecomposable summands in common. Then we say that $T^{\prime}$ is connected to $T$ by a cluster-tilting mutation.
Definition 25. A continuous surjection between compact spaces $f:K\longrightarrow L$ is called posex if there exists a pull-back diagram of continuous surjections $\begin{CD}K@>{f}>{}>L\\ @V{}V{}V@V{}V{}V\\ S@>{}>{}>R.\end{CD}$ with $R$ and $S$ metrizable compact spaces.
Definition 15. We say that a Banach space $\mathfrak{X}$ is tightly $\sigma$-filtered if there exists an ordinal $\lambda$ and a family $\{X_{\alpha}:\alpha\leq\lambda\}$ of subspaces of $\mathfrak{X}$ such that (1) $X_{\alpha}\subset X_{\beta}$ whenever $\alpha<\beta\leq\lambda$, (2) $X_{0}=0$ and $X_{\lambda}=X$, (3) $X_{\alpha+1}$ is a posex of $X_{\alpha}$ for every $\alpha<\lambda$, (4) $X_{\beta}=\overline{\bigcup_{\alpha<\beta}X_{\alpha}}$ for every limit ordinal $\beta\leq\lambda$.
Definition 3. We say that a Boolean algebra $\mathfrak{B}$ is tightly $\sigma$-filtered if there exists an ordinal $\lambda$ and a family $\{B_{\alpha}:\alpha\leq\lambda\}$ of subalgebras of $\mathfrak{B}$ such that (1) $B_{\alpha}\subset B_{\beta}$ whenever $\alpha<\beta\leq\lambda$, (2) $B_{0}=\{0,1\}$ and $B_{\lambda}=\mathfrak{B}$, (3) $B_{\alpha+1}$ is a posex of $B_{\alpha}$ for every $\alpha<\lambda$, (4) $B_{\beta}=\bigcup_{\alpha<\beta}B_{\alpha}$ for every limit ordinal $\beta\leq\lambda$.
Definition 13. Let $Y$ be a Banach space and let $S$ and $X$ be subspaces of $Y$. We say that $Y$ is the internal push-out of $S$ and $X$ if the following conditions hold: (1) $Y=\overline{S+X}$ (2) $\|x+s\|=\inf\{\|x+r\|+\|s-r\|:r\in S\cap X\}$ for every $x\in X$ and every $s\in S$.
Definition 2. An embedding of Boolean algebras $A\longrightarrow B$ is said to be a posex (push-out separable extension) if there exists a push-out diagram of embeddings $\begin{CD}A@>{}>{}>B\\ @A{}A{}A@A{}A{}A\\ R@>{}>{}>S\end{CD}$ such that $S$ and $R$ are countable.
Definition 19. Let $\mathfrak{X}$ be a (nonseparable) Banach space. An additive $\sigma$-skeleton of $\mathfrak{X}$ is a family $\mathcal{F}$ of subspaces of $\mathfrak{X}$ with the following properties: (1) $0\in\mathcal{F}$ (2) For every subfamily $\mathcal{G}\subset\mathcal{F}$, we have $\overline{span}\left(\bigcup\mathcal{G}\right)\in\mathcal{F}$. (3) For every infinite-dimensional $X\subset\mathfrak{X}$ there exists $Y\in\mathcal{F}$ with $X\subset Y\subset\mathfrak{X}$ and $dens(Y)=dens(X)$. (4) Each $X\in\mathcal{F}$ is a $\sigma$-subspace of $\mathfrak{X}$.
Definition 8. Let $\mathfrak{B}$ be a (uncountable) Boolean algebra. An additive $\sigma$-skeleton of $\mathfrak{B}$ is a family $\mathcal{F}$ of subalgebras of $\mathfrak{B}$ with the following properties: (1) $\{0,1\}\in\mathcal{F}$ (2) For every subfamily $\mathcal{G}\subset\mathcal{F}$, we have $\left\langle\bigcup\mathcal{G}\right\rangle\in\mathcal{F}$. (3) For every infinite subalgebra $A\subset\mathfrak{B}$, there exists $A^{\prime}\in\mathcal{F}$ such that with $A\subset A^{\prime}\subset\mathfrak{B}$ and $|A|=|A^{\prime}|$. (4) Every $A\in\mathcal{F}$ is a $\sigma$-subalgebra of $\mathfrak{B}$.
Definition 1. Let $B$ be a Boolean algebra and let $S$ and $A$ be subalgebras of $B$. We say that $B$ is the internal push-out of $S$ and $A$ if the following conditions hold: (1) $B=\langle S\cup A\rangle$. (2) For every $a\in A$ and every $s\in S$, if $a\wedge s=0$, then there exists $r\in A\cap S$ such that $a\leq r$ and $s\leq\overline{r}$.
Definition 26. A compact space $K$ is called pull-back generated if there exists a family $\{K_{\alpha}:\alpha\leq\xi\}$ of compact spaces and continuous surjections $\{f_{\alpha}^{\beta}:K_{\beta}\longrightarrow K_{\alpha}:\alpha\leq\beta\leq\xi\}$ such that (1) $K_{0}$ is a singleton and $K_{\xi}=K$, (2) $f_{\alpha}^{\alpha}$ is the identity map on $K_{\alpha}$, (3) $f_{\alpha}^{\beta}f_{\beta}^{\gamma}=f_{\alpha}^{\gamma}$ for $\alpha\leq\beta\leq\gamma\leq\xi$, (4) $f_{\alpha}^{\alpha+1}:K_{\alpha+1}\longrightarrow K_{\alpha}$ is posex for every $\alpha<\xi$, (5) If $\gamma\leq\xi$ is a limit ordinal and $x,y\in K_{\gamma}$ with $x\neq y$, then there exists $\beta<\gamma$ such that $f^{\gamma}_{\beta}(x)\neq f^{\gamma}_{\beta}(y)$ (this means that $K_{\gamma}$ is the inverse limit of the system below $\gamma$).
Definition 14. An isometric embedding of Banach spaces $X\longrightarrow Y$ is said to be a posex if there exists a push-out diagram of isometric embeddings $\begin{CD}X@>{}>{}>Y\\ @A{}A{}A@A{}A{}A\\ R@>{}>{}>S\end{CD}$ such that $S$ and $R$ are separable.
Definition 31. If $A$ is a subalgebra of $B$, $Q\subset A$ and $b\in B$, then we write $b\leq_{A}Q$ if $\{a\in A:b\leq a\}$ equals the filter generated by $Q$ in $A$. Similarly, we write $Q\leq_{A}b$ if $\{a\in A:a\leq b\}$ equals the ideal generated by $Q$ in $A$.
Definition 22. Suppose that we have a commutative diagram of continuous surjections between compact spaces, $\begin{CD}K@>{f}>{}>L\\ @V{g}V{}V@V{v}V{}V\\ S@>{u}>{}>R.\end{CD}$ We say that this is a pull-back diagram if the following conditions hold: (1) For every $x,y\in K$, if $x\neq y$, then either $f(x)\neq f(y)$ or $g(x)\neq g(y)$. (2) If we are given $x\in S$ and $y\in L$ such that $u(x)=v(y)$, then there exists $z\in K$ such that $f(z)=y$ and $g(z)=x$.
Definition 3.3. Let $\mathbb{V}$ and $\mathbb{V}^{\prime}$ be two Leibniz 2-algebras, a morphism from $\mathbb{V}$ to $\mathbb{V}^{\prime}$ consists of $\bullet$ a linear functor $F$ from the underlying $2$-vector space of $\mathbb{V}$ to that of $\mathbb{V}^{\prime}$, $\bullet$ a skewsymmetric natural transformation $F_{2}(x,y):F_{0}(l_{2}(x,y))\longrightarrow l_{2}^{\prime}(F_{0}(x),F_{0}(y)),$ such that $\displaystyle(F_{1}J_{x,y,z})(F_{2}(x,\left\llbracket y,z\right\rrbracket)-F_{% 2}(y,\left\llbracket x,z\right\rrbracket))(\left\llbracket F_{0}(x),F_{2}(y,z)% \right\rrbracket-\left\llbracket F_{0}(y),F_{2}(x,z)\right\rrbracket)$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle F_{2}(\left\llbracket x,y\right\rrbracket,z)(\left\llbracket F_{% 2}(x,y),F_{0}(z)\right\rrbracket)(J_{F_{0}(x),F_{0}(y),F_{0}(z)}),$ or in terms of diagram, $\xymatrix{F_{0}\left\llbracket\left\llbracket x,y\right\rrbracket,z\right% \rrbracket\ar[dd]^{F_{2}(\left\llbracket x,y\right\rrbracket,z)}\ar[rr]^{F_{1}% J_{x,y,z}}&&F_{0}(\left\llbracket x,\left\llbracket y,z\right\rrbracket\right% \rrbracket-\left\llbracket y,\left\llbracket x,z\right\rrbracket\right% \rrbracket)\ar[dd]_{F_{2}(x,\left\llbracket y,z\right\rrbracket)-F_{2}(y,\left% \llbracket x,z\right\rrbracket)}\\ &&\\ \left\llbracket F_{0}\left\llbracket x,y\right\rrbracket,F_{0}(z)\right% \rrbracket\ar[dd]^{\left\llbracket F_{2}(x,y),F_{0}(z)\right\rrbracket}&&\left% \llbracket F_{0}(x),F_{0}\left\llbracket y,z\right\rrbracket\right\rrbracket-% \left\llbracket F_{0}(y),F_{0}\left\llbracket x,z\right\rrbracket\right% \rrbracket\ar[dd]_{\left\llbracket F_{0}(x),F_{2}(y,z)\right\rrbracket-\left% \llbracket F_{0}(y),F_{2}(x,z)\right\rrbracket}\\ &&\\ \left\llbracket\left\llbracket F_{0}(x),F_{0}(y)\right\rrbracket,F_{0}(z)% \right\rrbracket\ar[rr]^{J_{F_{0}(x),F_{0}(y),F_{0}(z)}\qquad\qquad\quad}&&% \left\llbracket F_{0}(x),\left\llbracket F_{0}(y),F_{0}(z)\right\rrbracket% \right\rrbracket-\left\llbracket F_{0}(y),\left\llbracket F_{0}(x),F_{0}(z)% \right\rrbracket\right\rrbracket.}$
Definition 2.4. A crossed module of Leibniz algebras is a morphism of Leibniz algebras $\mu:\mathfrak{g}\longrightarrow\mathfrak{h}$ together with a representation of $\mathfrak{h}$ (consists of a left action and a right action satisfying the compatibility condition (1)) on $\mathfrak{g}$ such that for any $g,g^{\prime}\in\mathfrak{g},~{}h\in\mathfrak{h}$, the following equalities hold: $\displaystyle\mu(l_{h}g)$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle[h,\mu(g)]_{\mathfrak{h}},\quad\mu(r_{h}g)=[\mu(g),h]_{\mathfrak{% h}};$ $\displaystyle~{}l_{\mu(g)}g^{\prime}$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle[g,g^{\prime}]_{\mathfrak{g}}=r_{\mu(g^{\prime})}g;$ $\displaystyle l_{h}[g,g^{\prime}]_{\mathfrak{g}}$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle[l_{h}g,g^{\prime}]_{\mathfrak{g}}+[g,l_{h}g^{\prime}]_{\mathfrak% {g}};$ $\displaystyle r_{h}[g,g^{\prime}]_{\mathfrak{g}}$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle[g,r_{h}g^{\prime}]_{\mathfrak{g}}-[g^{\prime},r_{h}g];$ $\displaystyle~{}[l_{h}g+r_{h}g,g^{\prime}]_{\mathfrak{g}}$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle 0.$
Definition 2.9. Let $\mathcal{V}$ and $\mathcal{V}^{\prime}$ be $2$-term sh Leibniz algebras, a morphism $\mathfrak{f}$ from $\mathcal{V}$ to $\mathcal{V}^{\prime}$ consists of $\bullet$ linear maps $f_{0}:V_{0}\longrightarrow V_{0}^{\prime}$ and $f_{1}:V_{1}\longrightarrow V_{1}^{\prime}$ commuting with the differential, i.e. $f_{0}\circ\mathrm{d}=\mathrm{d}^{\prime}\circ f_{1};$ $\bullet$ a bilinear map $f_{2}:V_{0}\times V_{0}\longrightarrow V_{1}^{\prime}$, such that for all $x,y,z\in L_{0},~{}m\in L_{1}$, we have $\left\{\begin{array}[]{rll}l_{2}^{\prime}(f_{0}(x),f_{0}(y))-f_{0}l_{2}(x,y)&=% &\mathrm{d}^{\prime}f_{2}(x,y),\\ l_{2}^{\prime}(f_{0}(x),f_{1}(m))-f_{1}l_{2}(x,m)&=&f_{2}(x,\mathrm{d}m),\\ l_{2}^{\prime}(f_{1}(m),f_{0}(x))-f_{1}l_{2}(m,x)&=&f_{2}(\mathrm{d}m,x),\end{% array}\right.$ and $\displaystyle f_{1}(l_{3}(x,y,z))+l_{2}^{\prime}(f_{0}(x),f_{2}(y,z))-l_{2}^{% \prime}(f_{0}(y),f_{2}(x,z))-l_{2}^{\prime}(f_{2}(x,y),f_{0}(z))$ $\displaystyle-f_{2}(l_{2}(x,y),z)+f_{2}(x,l_{2}(y,z))-f_{2}(y,l_{2}(x,z))-l_{3% }^{\prime}(f_{0}(x),f_{0}(y),f_{0}(z))=0.$
Definition 2.2. A $2$-term sh Leibniz algebra $\mathcal{V}$ consists of the following data: $\bullet$ a complex of vector spaces $\mathcal{V}:V_{1}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{d}}}{{\longrightarrow}}V_{0},$ $\bullet$ bilinear maps $l_{2}:V_{i}\times V_{j}\longrightarrow V_{i+j}$, where $i+j\leq 1$, $\bullet$ a trilinear map $l_{3}:V_{0}\times V_{0}\times V_{0}\longrightarrow V_{1}$, such that for any $w,x,y,z\in V_{0}$ and $m,n\in V_{1}$, the following equalities are satisfied: $\rm(a)$ $\mathrm{d}l_{2}(x,m)=l_{2}(x,\mathrm{d}m),$ $\rm(b)$ $\mathrm{d}l_{2}(m,x)=l_{2}(\mathrm{d}m,x),$ $\rm(c)$ $l_{2}(\mathrm{d}m,n)=l_{2}(m,\mathrm{d}n),$ $\rm(d)$ $\mathrm{d}l_{3}(x,y,z)=l_{2}(x,l_{2}(y,z))-l_{2}(l_{2}(x,y),z)-l_{2}(y,l_{2}(x% ,z)),$ $\rm(e_{1})$ $l_{3}(x,y,\mathrm{d}m)=l_{2}(x,l_{2}(y,m))-l_{2}(l_{2}(x,y),m)-l_{2}(y,l_{2}(x% ,m)),$ $\rm(e_{2})$ $l_{3}(x,\mathrm{d}m,y)=l_{2}(x,l_{2}(m,y))-l_{2}(l_{2}(x,m),y)-l_{2}(m,l_{2}(x% ,y)),$ $\rm(e_{3})$ $l_{3}(\mathrm{d}m,x,y)=l_{2}(m,l_{2}(x,y))-l_{2}(l_{2}(m,x),y)-l_{2}(x,l_{2}(m% ,y)),$ $\rm(f)$ the Jacobiator identity: $\displaystyle l_{2}(w,l_{3}(x,y,z))-l_{2}(x,l_{3}(w,y,z))+l_{2}(y,l_{3}(w,x,z)% )+l_{2}(l_{3}(w,x,y),z)$ $\displaystyle-l_{3}(l_{2}(w,x),y,z)-l_{3}(x,l_{2}(w,y),z)-l_{3}(x,y,l_{2}(w,z))$ $\displaystyle+l_{3}(w,l_{2}(x,y),z)+l_{3}(w,y,l_{2}(x,z))-l_{3}(w,x,l_{2}(y,z)% )=0.$
Definition 6.1. A Dirac structure of the twisted Courant algebroid $(E,\left\langle\cdot,\cdot\right\rangle,\{\cdot,\cdot\},\rho,H)$ is a maximal isotropic subbundle $L$ such that the section space $\Gamma(L)$ is closed under the bracket operation $\{\cdot,\cdot\}$.
Definition 2.1. [29] A sh Leibniz algebra is a graded vector space $L=L_{0}\oplus L_{1}\oplus\cdots$ equipped with a system $\{l_{k}|~{}1\leq k<\infty\}$ of linear maps $l_{k}:\wedge^{k}L\longrightarrow L$ with degree $\deg(l_{k})=k-2$, where the exterior powers are interpreted in the graded sense and the following relation is satisfied: $\displaystyle\sum_{i+j=Const}\sum_{k\geq j}\sum_{\sigma}(-1)^{(k+1-j)(j-1)}(-1% )^{j(|x_{\sigma(1)}|+\cdots+|x_{\sigma(k-j)}|)}\sum_{\sigma}\mathrm{sgn}(% \sigma)\mathrm{Ksgn}(\sigma)$ $\displaystyle l_{i}(x_{\sigma(1)},\dots,x_{\sigma(k-j)},l_{j}(x_{\sigma(k+1-j)% },\dots,x_{\sigma(k)}),x_{\sigma(k+1)},\dots,x_{\sigma(i+j-1)})=0,$ where the summation is taken over all $(k-j,j-1)$-unshuffles and “$\mathrm{Ksgn}(\sigma)$” is the Koszul sign for a permutation $\sigma\in S_{k}$, i.e. $x_{1}\wedge x_{2}\wedge\cdots\wedge x_{k}=\mathrm{Ksgn}(\sigma)x_{\sigma(1)}% \wedge x_{\sigma(2)}\wedge\cdots\wedge x_{\sigma(k)}.$
Definition 2.7. A $2$-term sh Leibniz algebra $(V_{1}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\mathrm{d}}}{{\longrightarrow}}V_{0},l_{2},l_{3})$ is called skeletal if $\mathrm{d}=0$.
Definition 5.1. [13] A twisted Courant algebroid by a closed $4$-form $H$ is a vector bundle $E\longrightarrow M$, together with a fiber metric $\left\langle\cdot,\cdot\right\rangle$ (so we can identify $E$ with $E^{*}$), a bundle map $\rho:E\longrightarrow TM$ (called the anchor), a bilinear bracket operation (Dorfman bracket) $\{\cdot,\cdot\}$ on $\Gamma(E)$, and a closed $4$-form $H$ such that for any $e_{1},e_{2},e_{3}\in\Gamma(E)$, we have $\displaystyle\{e,e\}$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle\frac{1}{2}\rho^{*}d\left\langle e,e\right\rangle;$ $\displaystyle\rho(e_{1})\left\langle e_{2},e_{3}\right\rangle$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle\left\langle\{e_{1},e_{2}\},e_{3}\right\rangle+\left\langle e_{2}% ,\{e_{1},e_{3}\}\right\rangle;$ $\displaystyle\rho^{*}(i_{\rho(e_{1})\wedge\rho(e_{2})\wedge\rho(e_{3})}H)$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle\{e_{1},\{e_{2},e_{3}\}\}-\{\{e_{1},e_{2}\},e_{3}\}-\{e_{2},\{e_{% 1},e_{3}\}\},$ where $d$ is the usual de Rham differential operator and $\rho^{*}:T^{*}M\longrightarrow E^{*}$ is the dual map of $\rho$.
Definition 3.1. [3] A $2$-vector space is a category in the category $\mathrm{Vect}$.
Definition 3.2. A Leibniz $2$-algebra is a $2$-vector space $\mathbb{V}$ endowed with a bilinear functor (bracket) $\left\llbracket\cdot,\cdot\right\rrbracket:\mathbb{V}\times\mathbb{V}% \longrightarrow\mathbb{V}$ and a natural isomorphism $J_{x,y,z}$ for every $x,y,z\in\mathbb{V}_{0}$, $J_{x,y,z}:\left\llbracket\left\llbracket x,y\right\rrbracket,z\right\rrbracket% \longrightarrow\left\llbracket x,\left\llbracket y,z\right\rrbracket\right% \rrbracket-\left\llbracket y,\left\llbracket x,z\right\rrbracket\right\rrbracket,$ such that the following Jacobiator identity is satisfied: $\displaystyle J_{\left\llbracket w,x\right\rrbracket,y,z}(J_{w,x,\left% \llbracket y,z\right\rrbracket}-\left\llbracket y,J_{w,x,z}\right\rrbracket)=$ $\displaystyle\left\llbracket J_{w,x,y},z\right\rrbracket(J_{w,\left\llbracket x% ,y\right\rrbracket,z}-J_{x,\left\llbracket w,y\right\rrbracket,z})(\left% \llbracket w,J_{x,y,z}\right\rrbracket-J_{x,y,\left\llbracket w,z\right% \rrbracket}-\left\llbracket x,J_{w,y,z}\right\rrbracket+J_{w,y,\left\llbracket x% ,z\right\rrbracket}),$ or, in terms of a diagram, $\xymatrix{&\left\llbracket\left\llbracket\left\llbracket w,x\right\rrbracket,y% \right\rrbracket,z\right\rrbracket\ar[dr]^{J_{\left\llbracket w,x\right% \rrbracket,y,z}}\ar[dl]_{\left\llbracket J_{w,x,y},z\right\rrbracket}&\\ \left\llbracket\left\llbracket w,\left\llbracket x,y\right\rrbracket\right% \rrbracket,z\right\rrbracket-\left\llbracket\left\llbracket x,\left\llbracket w% ,y\right\rrbracket\right\rrbracket,z\right\rrbracket\ar[dd]^{J_{w,\left% \llbracket x,y\right\rrbracket,z}-J_{x,\left\llbracket w,y\right\rrbracket,z}}% &&\left\llbracket\left\llbracket w,x\right\rrbracket,\left\llbracket y,z\right% \rrbracket\right\rrbracket-\left\llbracket y,\left\llbracket\left\llbracket w,% x\right\rrbracket,z\right\rrbracket\right\rrbracket\ar[dd]_{J_{w,x,\left% \llbracket y,z\right\rrbracket}-\left\llbracket y,J_{w,x,z}\right\rrbracket}\\ &&\\ P\ar[rr]^{\left\llbracket w,J_{x,y,z}\right\rrbracket-J_{x,y,\left\llbracket w% ,z\right\rrbracket}-\left\llbracket x,J_{w,y,z}\right\rrbracket+J_{w,y,\left% \llbracket x,z\right\rrbracket}}&&Q}$ where $P$ and $Q$ are given by $\displaystyle P$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle\left\llbracket w,\left\llbracket\left\llbracket x,y\right% \rrbracket,z\right\rrbracket\right\rrbracket-\left\llbracket\left\llbracket x,% y\right\rrbracket,\left\llbracket w,z\right\rrbracket\right\rrbracket-\left% \llbracket x\left\llbracket\left\llbracket w,y\right\rrbracket,z\right% \rrbracket\right\rrbracket+\left\llbracket\left\llbracket w,y\right\rrbracket,% \left\llbracket x,z\right\rrbracket\right\rrbracket,$ $\displaystyle Q$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle\left\llbracket w,\left\llbracket x,\left\llbracket y,z\right% \rrbracket\right\rrbracket\right\rrbracket-\left\llbracket x,\left\llbracket w% ,\left\llbracket y,z\right\rrbracket\right\rrbracket\right\rrbracket-\left% \llbracket y,\left\llbracket w,\left\llbracket x,z\right\rrbracket\right% \rrbracket\right\rrbracket+\left\llbracket y,\left\llbracket x,\left\llbracket w% ,z\right\rrbracket\right\rrbracket\right\rrbracket.$
Definition 6.3. A bi-vector field $\pi\in\mathfrak{X}^{2}(M)$ is called an $h$-twisted Poisson structure if (38) holds. $(M,\pi)$ is called an $h$-twisted Poisson manifold if $\pi$ is an $h$-twisted Poisson structure.
Definition 18 A category ${\cal C}$ is said to be trivial iff, for any objects $A$, $B$ the set $hom(A,B)$ is a singleton.
Definition 12 An A-category with unit object is said to be a T-category iff for every pair of objects $A$, $B$ there exists a tensor product $\kappa_{A,B}:A,B\rightarrow$ $A\otimes B$.
Definition 25 Let $A$, $B$ and $C$ be objects In a BT-category. Note that ${id}_{A}\otimes{u}_{B,C}:$ $A\otimes B\rightarrow A\otimes(B\oplus C)$ and ${id}_{A}\otimes{v}_{B,C}:$ $A\otimes C\rightarrow A\otimes(B\oplus C)$. We shall define ${x}_{A,B,C}=$ $[{id}_{A}\otimes{u}_{B,C}\ \ {id}_{A}\otimes{v}_{B,C}]$. In other words, ${x}_{A,B,C}:$ $(A\otimes B)\oplus(A\otimes C)\rightarrow$ $A\otimes(B\oplus C)$ is the only arrow such that: $x_{A,B,C}\circ{u}_{A\otimes B,A\otimes C}\ =\ {id}_{A}\otimes{u}_{B,C}$ $x_{A,B,C}\circ{v}_{A\otimes B,A\otimes C}\ =\ {id}_{A}\otimes{v}_{B,C}.$ Similarly we define $y_{A,B,C}:(B\otimes A)\oplus(C\otimes A)\rightarrow$ $(B\oplus C)\otimes A$ as $y_{A,B,C}=$ $[{u}_{B,C}\otimes{id}_{A}\ \ {v}_{B,C}\otimes{id}_{A}]$.
Definition 9 In an A-category with unit object $I$, an arrow $f:A\rightarrow B$ is said to preserve scalar products iff for any preparations $a,b:I\rightarrow A$, one has $\langle f\circ b\mid f\circ a\rangle=$ $\langle b\mid a\rangle$. It is said to be an isometry iff $sq(f\circ a)=$ $sq(a)$.
Definition 22 An A-category with unit object is said to be normalizable iff, for any object $A$ and any preparation $a:I\rightarrow A$ there is some normalized preparation $n:I\rightarrow A$ and some scalar $s:I\rightarrow I$ such that $a=$ $n\circ s$.
Definition 6 A preparation is said to be normalized iff it is right-unitary.
Definition 15 In an Az-category, 1. arrows $f:A\rightarrow C$ and $g:B\rightarrow C$ with common co-domain are said to be orthogonal iff the two equivalent conditions below hold: • ${g}^{\star}\circ f=$ ${0}_{A,B}$, • ${f}^{\star}\circ g=$ ${0}_{B,A}$, and 2. arrows $f:C\rightarrow A$ and $g:C\rightarrow B$ with common domain are said to be orthogonal iff the two equivalent conditions below hold: • $g\circ{f}^{\star}=$ ${0}_{A,B}$, • $f\circ{g}^{\star}=$ ${0}_{B,A}$, The equivalence of both conditions follows from Lemma 18. Note that for parallel arrows $f,g:A\rightarrow B$ both cases 1 and 2 give the same answer, so that no confusion can arise. In fact, we shall use case 1 only when $f$ and $g$ are right-unitary, i.e., subspace injections, and case 2 only when $f$ and $g$ are left-unitary, i.e., projections on subspaces, but the definition is more general.
Definition 7 An object $I$ in an A-category is said to be a unit object iff 1. for any object $A$ there is at least one normalized preparation of sort $I\rightarrow A$, 2. for any objects $A$, $B$ and any arrows $f,g:A\rightarrow B$, if for any preparation $a:I\rightarrow A$ one has $f\circ a=$ $g\circ a$ then one has $f=g$, 3. for every object $A$ and every scalar $s:I\rightarrow I$ there is an arrow $s_{A}:$ $A\rightarrow A$ such that • for any preparation $a:I\rightarrow A$ one has $a\circ s=$ $s_{A}\circ a$, and • for any destruction $b:A\rightarrow I$ one has $s\circ b=$ $b\circ s_{A}$. Note that property 2 implies that this characterizes the arrow ${s}_{A}$ in a unique way.
Definition 20 Let $A$, $B$ be objects in a B-category. If $f,g:A\rightarrow B$ then we define the arrow $f+g:A\rightarrow B$ by $f+g=$ $\nabla_{B}\circ(f\oplus g)\circ\Delta_{A}$.
Definition 27 In a Q-category, for every arrow $f:A\rightarrow B$ we define the arrow ${f}^{-}:A\rightarrow B$ to be the arrow $f\circ{{1}^{-}}_{A}=$ ${{1}^{-}}_{B}\circ f$. The equality follows from Lemma 6.
